<HEADLINE>
Road accidents claim 27 lives as Thais celebrating New Year
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
BANGKOK, April 10 (Xinhua)
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At least 27 people have been 
killed and 754 others wounded in road accidents as some people 
began to return home Friday to celebrate the traditional Songkran 
festival, local press reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the dead were young people and 75 percent of the 
accidents were caused by motorcycles, Deputy Interior Minister 
Somchai Sunthornwat was quoted by Bangkok Post newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
On April 8, 2004, 31 people died and as many as 2,730 were 
injured in road accidents.
</P>
<P>
During this year's Songkran holiday from April 8 to 17, more 
than 91,000 officials were involved in the accident prevention 
work. And some 3,800 check points will be set up on highways where
most accidents occur, he said.
</P>
<P>
Motorcyclists who drink or do not wear crash helmets, 
passengers who do not put on safety belts and people who drive 
over the speed limit were regarded as violating  traffic rules.
</P>
